{#- VARIANT DETAIL (definition) — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="qbo-feat-chart-of-accounts-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">What the QuickBooks Online chart of accounts is, plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>The chart of accounts is the complete list of accounts your business uses to record what it owns, owes, earns, and spends. In QuickBooks Online it lives under the gear menu, and every transaction you enter &mdash; an invoice, a bill, a bank-feed charge, a journal entry &mdash; has to post to one of these accounts. Nothing in your books exists outside the chart of accounts.</p>
      <p>Each account is organized two ways. It has an <em>account type</em> &mdash; asset, liability, equity, income, or expense &mdash; which is the broad bucket that decides whether the account shows on the Balance Sheet or the Profit &amp; Loss. And beneath the type it has a <em>detail type</em>, a more specific classification QuickBooks uses to know how the account behaves and where it sits on your financial statements. Choosing the right type and detail type is what makes the reports come out correctly; the wrong type puts an account in the wrong place on every report it touches.</p>
      <p>The reason structure matters so much is that the chart of accounts is the framework all your reports inherit. Your <a href="/glossary/chart-of-accounts/">Profit &amp; Loss and Balance Sheet</a> are not separate creations &mdash; they are the chart of accounts, totaled and arranged by type. Build the list well and the financials read clearly; build it carelessly and no amount of tidy data entry makes the reports legible. We describe how QuickBooks Online actually behaves &mdash; we don&rsquo;t claim capabilities the feature doesn&rsquo;t have, and structure decisions carry tax-reporting implications that your CPA should confirm.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

